segments.text: A lot of times you drop your ruck in first and then you come down on top of it rather than have it on your back because of the extra weight and stuff like that.

But we normally in our missions we carry what they call just like the fights where you go with just a shoulder harness type thing with a couple of canteens and a couple of rounds of ammunition, cases of ammunition and stuff.
So we really didn't carry that much.
I walked point quite often in the jungle area where it was very dense in the mountains and stuff especially.
I walked point with a 12-gauge shotgun.

Most of the time I carried an M16, but in cases where it was real dense jungle where we were actually cutting our way through with machetes and stuff, you'd walk point with something that would kill in a short area.
At one time I carried a grease gun, which was an automatic .45 caliber gun.

thing which only is only deadly at about 50 yards or less you know it doesn't have a very long distance on it i always carried a 45 caliber pistol you know standard service issue pistol uh most of the time carried the m16 but it just depended on the situation i carried m60 a little bit i was a little bit small for carrying it but i carried it a few times when when you walked point did you um
Did you ever carry your rucksack?
Yeah.
No matter where you were, you carried your stuff.
Do you ever felt like that was ineffective and bundled you down?
Did you learn how to work with that?
You learned you had to carry what you had.
Nobody would carry your food for you or your water.
If you wanted food and water, you carried it yourself.
Some guys lived on less than others.
At times, after I really got orientated in the country, we would actually go up to

rivers or blue lines we call them and throw a hand grenade in the river and kill fish and we actually eat fish or rice like the locals and therefore we wouldn't be smelling any different from what the Vietnamese would smell you know any kind of odor anything given off is from cooking if we were cooking you know our sea rations or something you know you could smell that and it was definitely a different odor so a lot of times if we knew we were going to be an area where we could get fish or something like that we would
not take as much sea rations.
So from that standpoint we didn't have to carry near as much stuff.

When I got to the first calve we ate mostly lerps there which is a long-range patrol which is a dried food where all you had to do is add water to it and you could heat your water and put it in there or just do it cold.
So really in those lerps you could carry
A lot of LURPs and almost no weight at all because it was a freeze-dried food, so there was no weight to it whatsoever.
But those were mainly for the special mission type stuff.
Your normal infantry units didn't get those.
They had to carry their normal cans of C-rations and stuff like that.
So it was an extra weight type deal.
But, you know, it just depended on the mission and the length of time.
Sometimes after a couple of weeks out in the field, they'd drop us a new set of clothes, and, you know, we'd get different changes of, you know, stuff, boots or socks or whatever, you know, that way.
Did the new set of clothes have a detergent smell to them?
Oh, they weren't new.
They were just...
They were clean, I guess.
Let me put it that way.
They drop a bundle of clothes, and you dig out something that might fit you, and you put it on.
But it was clean clothes.
After two or three weeks without bathing, you start smelling real bad, and your socks stand up by themselves and stuff like that.
But there again, you get used to it, and it really doesn't affect you a whole lot.
That was something that a lot of guys accepted that a lot easier than others, but it's something you just have to accept and realize you can go now.
There were some areas we could bathe in the streams and rivers and try to keep clean, but, you know, you just go and go and go, and, you know, you don't really worry about your personal hygiene.
You worry about staying alive.
Did the company, somebody in the company ever carry a motor or any, what kind of other weapons did you carry other than personal weapons?
Well, they carried, like I was saying earlier, a lot of people carried the laws.
They carried 20-millimeter guns.
grenade launcher type things.
The M60 machine gun, every squad had an M60 guy.
Some guys carried other type of hand things, but probably the M60 was the biggest, you know, probably did the most damage type thing.

You know, they carried rounds and rounds of that, and usually the ammo from that, you'd either carry it in a hand metal canister, or they would hook it together and cross it across your chest, just like a
You know, you see your banditos or whatever carry their, you know, strings of ammo.
And usually carrying on your chest was easier because you had your hands free.
And if you had to hand carry a pouch of ammo, you know, your hand was always taken up with something in your hand.
So they'd take it out of there and crisscross across their chest and hook it on.
Then all they had to do was unsnap it, lay it in there, and go.
You know, it was real easy to feed in and go that way.
Normally, there was not very many.
If we were going out and definitely setting up a sniper type thing with a starlight scope, we might carry an M14 or two.
And they were a lot more accurate as a sniper rifle.
And had scopes on everything on them.
Those were strictly sniper rifles.
Were they night scopes?
Starlight scope, night scope, yeah.
We had those available to us.
They were really, really nice.
But that would really be the biggest thing.
Of course, the .50 cals, if we were ever moving in a convoy on the roads and stuff, the Jeeps all had .50 cals on them.
You know, some of the choppers had .50 cals mounted in them as door guns.
Most of them had M60s, but some of them had .50 cals.
The Chinooks had .50 cals in them.
And, of course, your choppers and stuff, a lot of those had the 20-millimeter cannons and rockets and, you know, the machine guns and stuff set up in those.
But as far as our actual personal weaponry, it was mostly just handguns as all we, you know, just light weapons that we carried ourselves.
What equipment was most effective?
for whatever purpose it served in, what equipment did y'all have to carry that was completely ineffective?
Was there any?
Was it allowable to ditch what you knew would not be effective?
We pretty much could pick what we wanted to carry.
Okay.
And, I mean, you know, we all wanted to carry frags or hand grenades.
Most of us had to carry at least two smokes.
And this would be for different reasons.
We almost all had to carry at least one tear gas grenade.
What did you use tear gas for?
Normally put it down the caves or bunker complexes, whatever you want to call them.
We'd go into a bunker complex and pop gas and put it in there.
Most of us did not carry gas masks.
It wasn't prominent or necessary.
They were issued to you, but usually you lost them real fast and didn't carry them.
We did, some guys carried them more than others, you know, it depends on where you were in the area.
Usually, other than that, a couple of first aid pouches and your water and food and, you know, your own personal M16, you know, shells or whatever you were carrying at the time that way.
But you could go back to your fire base and pretty much go over to the ammo bunker and supply anything you wanted, carry what you wanted.
Some guys were more gung-ho than others, and they carried a lot more stuff, but that's something you kind of learn.

And I was fortunate that I was kind of led by the hand by a sergeant when I first went in, and he kind of said, you don't need this, you need this, you don't need this, you need this, and throw this away, you don't need that.
How long had the sergeant been in there?
He'd been there for, he was on his second tour, so he was really in his second year, I guess.
Did he volunteer for it?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, he re-upped and went back in a whole nine yards, so.
And he was E5, no, not E5, E6.
He was an E6.
Was he a shake and bake?
No, no, no, no.
Okay.
No, he had got it through the grade type thing.
He had not gone to NCO school or nothing like that.
He was just an average Joe type guy that had moved up through the grades and not had any schooling part or anything like that.
Yeah, he basically learned it by the seat of his pants.
And he had been higher and been demoted.
You know, that was kind of normal realm.
You know, you go up and down, up and down, and rank like crazy over there.

and well you you get article 15s you know you go out and get drunk and shoot up somebody or something or whatever and not only kill somebody but i mean you know go and shoot up a something in town you might go into one of the villages and shoot up a bar or something like that and they oh man i'm gonna knock two stripes off of you and demote you and then you have to go back and two months later you get your stripes back or something like that you know that's our thing but those guys they they raised a lot of you know havoc with the locals and stuff like that but
There was all kinds of reasons for going up and down in rank.
Most people, they really didn't care a lot of what they did one way or another.
They were out there just trying to survive.
When you say most people, are you talking about?
The grunts, the infantry soldiers, yeah.
What about the leaders?
The leader guys, most officers were really intelligent people.
Most of them were college guys.
Their biggest problem was they thought they knew more than they did.
They really didn't have a, I don't know, seventh sense or whatever you want to call it.
They didn't have any street knowledge of the jungle.
They had learned it all in a book, and they had no practical knowledge of what they were doing.
You know, you get out there in a situation, and, you know, the lieutenant says, well, let's charge or something like that.
And everybody looked at that guy and said, you go ahead, brother.
You go ahead.
We're sitting here.
You know, we're not going nowhere.
You know, that's our thing.
But, I mean, well, it says in page six and six of the, you know, quota deal, we're supposed to get up and run now or something like that, you know.
That was the type of guy you'd run into, and the lieutenants especially, they would come over and we'd call them cherry lieutenants.
And we, you know, very seldom...
kept more than weeks at a time.
If they stayed a month, they were really lucky.
The lieutenants, they would either get shot by the enemy or possibly inflict a wound by their own side.
We'll get back to some of that stuff later.
We did sort of sidetrack here, but the equipment is what we were originally on.
And I guess to answer the one question, you never had to take anything that you felt was ineffective?
No, no, not at all.
No, we always carried what we wanted to.
There was no forcing there.
Like I said, they pretty much wanted you to carry frags and smokes, but that was stuff you wanted to carry anyway, so there was really no problem there at all.
As an intelligence analyst, could you in any way, shape, or form see the effects of the defoliant and the B-52, just the general B-52 strikes throughout all the Ho Chi Minh Trail and everything?
Yeah, I could see the reason for it.
And as an infantry soldier, too.
Right, right.
Could you yourself at that point see the effect it had on you personally?
Right.
If it did.
I could see the reasoning for it.
Okay.

Definitely in the thick jungles and stuff, the defoliants, you know, if we knew there was an area where the troop movement was heavy and, you know, you could not find them or see them or whatever, the only alternative you had was to go in there and spray or call a B-52 strike.
And I personally feel, you know, and usually this area that it was done in was a dense, dense jungle.
There was no villages near it.
There was no habitat.
So it wasn't affecting anybody's livelihood or anything like that.
This is in the mountains or the middle of nowhere.
I mean, granted, it did kill stuff.
I'm not saying it was right by any means, but it definitely had a purpose, and I think it served its purpose well.
It probably, you know, if anything, you know, if they would have done more than what they did, probably would have stepped things up more, especially the B-52 strikes.
Those guys, you come in with a B-52 strike in a bumper complex,
And you'd literally wipe out companies of NVA or something if you hit them right.
Because, you know, if the bunkers collapsed, depending on how they were dug, you know, you'd cave in on them and just smother them and kill them.
Because that was their livelihood was to dig in and go down.
And that was the only thing they could do would be go down.
If they stayed on the surface with a B-52 strike, they were dead.
And so it was a situation that usually the defoliant, if you clear out an area where they were actually at,

you know they had nowhere to go but down to so you can find the complex is a lot easier you know so you could find that bunker complex you could go in that bunker complex and flush them out and that was that was like going into their home you found out where they lived and you can get them and you know we had fire bases which were sitting out in the open where they always knew where we were but we never knew where they were so the defoliants definitely had their purpose now granted the spraying on top of our troops and
People going into areas right after they were sprayed and stuff, obviously with Agent Orange issues and stuff, was not good.
I personally never got sprayed directly.
I did go into areas that had been sprayed freshly.
It was obviously a very, very toxic chemical.
Some of the soldiers knew that too.
Well, we knew what it was.
We knew it was a defoliant, but we really didn't think that it would hurt us.
if you follow what I'm saying there.
I mean, you know, just like spraying bug spray at home, you know, you know you're killing a bug, but is this stuff going to kill me?
You know, you really never think about that too much.
You know it has a purpose.
It's after killing the leaves and the bushes and the trees so you can see, but will it really kill you or affect you?
There are people who have never fallen dead around when it happened, but, you know, 20 years now after the fact, there's people affected by it, obviously.
So, you know, it's a situation that
You don't think of a long haul.
You think of the immediate response.
And I think that's why it happened.
They wanted something that would work at the time.
And it did.
It served its purpose well.
And, you know, personally, I think it probably was well done.
You know, there's always mistakes and incidents that you say, oh, I wish we wouldn't have sprayed then or we should have got those troops out at that time or something like that.
So, you know, people did get affected by it.
But overall, I think it was done right.
I don't really...
see anything negative there whatsoever.
It did save American lives.
I think so.
In the long run, it was definitely a necessity.
And, you know, you can't really second guess it now because it's been so long, but you go back and look and say, you know, those guys might still be sitting there in those bunker complexes.
We would have never found them.
But by defoliating, we found the bunker complex or calling B-52 strike, we were able to knock that complex out.
Speaking of bunker complexes...
Was it standard Army rules to send a guy down there first?
No, not really.
That was pretty much on your own.
You pretty much, each individual squad, you normally would, depending on the situation, you'd call back and tell them what you found.
Okay.
Okay, report in.
Who do you report in to?
You report in usually to your captain or colonel.
Usually it was just like on our missions, lieutenant would be the only officer out there with us.
Okay, the lieutenant would call in, tell the captain what happened.
The captain would tell the colonel.
They'd call back and say, okay, send some guy down there and check it out.
Or pull back and call an artillery.

Okay, so depending on the situation or where it was, if it looked like it was a live bunker, that there might still be people in it, we would usually pull back and call an artillery and try to blow it up a little bit and then go in and try to find stuff.
Or they might send dogs out to run through it or something like that.
You know, they had trained

dogs over there that did that sort of thing so you know there was there was all kinds of different things but no it wasn't standard procedure send somebody down immediately we normally would back up and call in and ask for what they want us to do mention artillery now that that brings up a question and the question about artillery since you did spend so much time in the jungle
Did you ever see cases where the artillery was ineffective because it was exploding in the treetops?
Oh, yeah.
Was that frequent?
Did you account for that by saying send in twice the amount of rounds?
Well, you just kept calling for it if you needed it, and if it blew up the trees, eventually the trees would be blown up and it would get down to where you needed it.
Okay.
So, I mean, you just had to call for more of it.
Okay.
But, yes, we did see it.
especially in the real dense jungle and stuff like that.
Did any of the fragments ever hit?
We would get shrapnel from it, yes.
As a matter of fact, I had one small wound in my back from fragments from a, I think it was probably a 105 round or something.
It was an altar we called in that hit real close to us, and just little pieces of metal would fly up and hit you and burn you more than anything else.
It wasn't anything severe.
But that stuff would be dangerous if you were close enough to it.
And the white phosphorus was really bad.
I don't know if you've ever seen a white phosphorus.
We call them willy peats.
They come in and hit, and you see the white smoke stuff going up.
And if that stuff ever hit you and got on your body, it would just burn right through you.
It was terrible.
That's all it was, was just heat?
It was heat, white phosphorus is what it was, the actual chemical phosphorus.
And it would be burning.
When it hit, it would explode and go out.
And if that stuff, if you were anywhere near a white phosphorus when it went off and got on you, I mean, it would just hit you and just start burning your skin and eating you up.
On which situations would you call in white phosphorus?
If we knew of a large concentrate of enemy on the ground.
And you had to call it in?
We called in, you know, what really beats.
What we normally would do, first couple of rounds, we'd call in marker rounds, and they'd come in and hit.
And if we knew it was right on the money where they were, then we'd say, okay, shell it with white phosphorus.
Go for it.
And we knew, say, like, if we had them surrounded and we knew they were there and we wanted to get them out or kill them, we'd call in one of these rounds of white phosphorus.
And, man, they'd just stand up and start running and screaming, you know, just burning them like crazy.
I mean, you can see them.
You know, it was very obvious, very effective, very effective stuff.
And the purpose that it served.
Yes, definitely.
Is there any equipment that we haven't discussed that?
Not really.
There were some flamethrowers that we saw every once in a while, but this was more specialized stuff that I didn't personally come in contact with.
I saw it several times.
There was basically special units like your mortar units.
They would carry mortars on their backs out there, and they'd set up in there and pop mortars and stuff.
They had different things, and then the actual artillery guys had their different cannons and stuff.
The 105s and 155s would shoot stuff.
And they would carry them out there sometimes in the jungle with helicopters and set them down and shoot.
You know, if they had to get to a special area, they'd set up a little area and start shooting, you know, and set up a little base of their own and, you know, form their own little fire base.

So, you know, you'd be sitting there and if you, you know, were in an area where they couldn't get to you by anything like that, they might set something up to shoot or they might call in, the Air Force might come in and,
The Air Force had what I call a push and pull, like a Cessna had a motor in the front and back, and they carried rockets on the wings.
And those things were really good for blowing up bridges.
And then they could come in real accurately and shoot these rockets off these wings of these Cessnas and blow up bridges that we'd come across.
Did you ever see any of them go down?
Were they susceptible to... Yeah, they were fairly susceptible, although they'd fly low and fast, like the choppers.
There again, your choppers, your
Actual troop transport, Huey, wasn't that effective because it was so slow.
But they had what I call a loach, which is a smaller chopper that carried 20-millimeter cannon and, of course, your door gun or your either .50 caliber or your M60s machine guns.
And they were very active and fast.
They were kind of a search-and-destroy type thing.
And then, of course, the actual Cobras, the gunships they call them,
Those guys, man, they could come in and just unbelievably put out a spray of bullets and stuff.
Usually if we were going into an area that we felt was enemy and we had to sit down, the Cobras would go in first and just blow up the area.
I mean, just boom, boom, boom, boom, boom, blow it up.
And then we'd come in and get out and try to secure the area before the troop movement would come in.
But the Cobras were really...
put out a lot of firepower.
They were very effective weapons.
Two things to have on your side.
Yes, definitely.
All right, we're going to sort of switch subjects here and start speaking about leaders.
Okay.
Who or what was the highest rank in the fire base?
Usually colonels.
They had what they call a full bird colonel, you know, and that was usually the highest rank on the fire base.

uh... what was his average rotation how long would he be around most colonels would stay for quite some time they they were the quote there again lifers and uh... you know i'd various well both two instances in the hunter first and the uh... first cab well i only worked with one colonel in both places so i mean we didn't have really a turnover of my direct colonels you know that way they usually stayed right there the colonel was you know they pretty much
stayed in command of that particular unit, you know, at that time.
Now, were there any Fragans?
And also, what rank did they involve?
Yes, quite a bit.
There's more in the lower ranks with the actual lieutenants, a few captains every once in a while, but mainly lieutenants.
And it would usually happen either in the field or in the rear areas after a conflict out in the field, basically.
Usually as far as the instance where in the field somebody might get shot in the back rather than a frag.
And your fragging instance happened in your hoochers at night and stuff like that.
They would actually be asleep or somebody would go through and just drop a frag in your thing.
There was fragging incidents in the local bars and stuff every once in a while.
If they knew a guy would be in there that they wanted to get, they would actually frag the whole bar.
so it wouldn't be a direct hit on one particular person.
So nobody could really be blamed for one thing.
And then at that time also, they could blame it on the VC or local villagers or some shit like that.
So, but it, you know, we knew, you know, the guys that talk bad about him in the company, they get high on drugs and they say, I'm going to kill that guy.
You know, he's not going to go back out on another mission with me.
And, you know, next day they got to be dead, you know.
So you knew it happened.
Yeah, but nobody ever proved it or anything.
There was never any court-martials or any direct
things from any instance that I was aware of.
Although, we went through lots of lieutenants up there, especially in six months.
I probably went through eight, nine lieutenants in six months' time.
Among the DMZ?
In the DMZ, yeah.
Did you, I guess you didn't have to work with any shake-and-bake lieutenants when you were at the first cab?
No, not really.
I was working more with the higher officers and, you know, lifers and stuff, and really didn't see it that much there.
Everybody was more of the seasoned veteran kind
when I was in the first cab where when I was in the 101st, it was more of the rookies and the shake and bakes, like you said, and the guys that really didn't know what they were doing.
They'd just been to a training school and learned it out of a book.
They had no practical knowledge.
When I was working in intelligence, most intelligence guys had years of service, and a lot of them had been unarmed for one or two tours.
So I was really the rookie.
I was very fortunate to get in at the right time when I got there.
I just was at the right place at the right time for those deals.
I got real lucky to get actually pulled out of the, you know, regular, you know, foot soldier type activity and start flying a little more that way.
As an infantry soldier, who'd you listen to up along the DMZ and the 103rd?
Mostly the sergeants.
Very seldom listen to the officers.
Did you yourself just ignore the officers too?
Pretty much, yeah.
Okay.
You really...
I kind of got taken under the wing of that sergeant, like I was saying, and you can tell who knows what.
And then you listen to your own gut feeling, too.
You know whether that lieutenant's telling you the right thing or not.
Now, a lot of guys didn't know, and a lot of guys died.
It's just simple as that.
I'm not saying they were wrong, but at the same time, people died because of what they told them to do.
So, you know, I never...

quote directly disobeyed a direct order although I would question it a lot of times and say let's talk about this guys you know or you know some instances you know they would say do something and I wouldn't directly do it I would do what I felt was right within the means of what they were saying well um I basically just in a day type thing we would be moving during the day time
We would have to walk so many feet apart, supposedly, and more or less in a certain pattern.
And we had hand signals because there was no talking or anything like this.
So we'd be going along, and all of a sudden we'd take incoming fire, sniper fire.
We basically hit the ground initially and spread out.
And we would sit there, and of course the lieutenant would try to find out where it came from

all right then he would say okay you you and you let's go and you say yeah wait a minute do we really want to get up and start running with this guy shooting at us or not and so you know usually the sergeant would enter act at that time and say wait a minute wait a minute and the sergeant would get there and talk to the lieutenant and they sit there and talk it over and then we might do something different or if he says let's go this way
I might go that way, but I wouldn't necessarily go with them.
I might do my own little maneuvering or something like that.
I would basically do what I wanted to do within the means of what I was told.
I reckon that's where you're tracking.
Right, exactly.
You're a little bit more comfortable going away from the group.
Right.
I wasn't a loner by any means.
I wasn't a gung-ho guy.
I was just trying to stay alive.
A lot of times, we got hit one time and
He said he wanted us all to get up and run.
He said, let's pull out, let's go.
And I, you know, I looked at the sergeant and we both shook our heads and we ain't going nowhere.
You know, and Lieutenant says, let's go, let's go, let's go.
And he said, bye, go.
So Lieutenant and about six guys took off.
The other six of us stayed there.
Those guys got killed.
Wow.
You know, and, you know, we just knew
Our best bet was to stay put because we had no idea how many enemy were out there.
We didn't know what the force was.
We didn't know where they were.
We knew we were being shot at.
We were pinned down.
Our best bet was to call an artillery or just wait them out and find out where they were and try to, you know, get them.
But he wanted to run, and he ran.
He ran right into an ambush, and they blew him down, man, mowed him all down.
And, you know, as it turned out, we called in artillery, and the guys pulled back, and then they flew in and picked us up in a chopper, and we got out of there without a scratch.
So, you know, it's just common sense more than anything else.
The lieutenants just didn't seem to have it.
Did any higher-ranking officers go out with y'all?
Captain was the highest that ever really directly went in the field with me.
And normally the

captains yeah the captains you know they basically you know they would run everything you know when they were out there and the deal with the captains usually you know it would be in a large masses so it would be like a major movement of five or six squads or whatever in the company so I never directly personally got associated with the captains
What I saw with the fragging of the captains was with the sergeants, because your sergeants and your lieutenants would interact with the captain basically on their talking.
You know, you'd come in and they'd have little pow-wows and they'd say, okay, let's go do this.
And usually what would happen was, you know, some guy's getting short, didn't want to go out on night patrol or something like that, and the captain would say, you've got to go.
And, you know, I ain't going nowhere, man.
You know, I'm staying in here.
I'm going to go out and get my blow away.
So the next thing you know, the captain got shot or he got fragged or something, you know.
And usually that would happen with the sergeants more than the lower rank.
Where the lower ranker guys, the privates, PFCs, whatever, specialists, they would be the ones that seemed to be taking care of the lieutenants.
So it was kind of a chain of command type thing that way.
What happened?
What do you think happened?
Why did this blatant breakdown of chain of command?
Well...
I really, in myself, I personally never got mad enough or upset enough at anyone to try to shoot them.
I disagreed with them a lot, and I didn't do that many drugs over there, so I was straight, especially in the field.
But I think drugs might have had a lot to do with it.
A guy would get really doped up on coke or heroin, be shooting heroin like crazy.
And, you know, he didn't want to go out there and get shot at.
And this guy's telling the direct order to go get shot.
And he might bust him.
They might give him Article 15 or something.
So here's this lieutenant or captain saying, you ain't going out there, man.
You're in trouble.
You know, the guy's all messed up on drugs.
So they send him back to the rear area, bust him.
And next time the captain comes back to the rear area, he's dead.
You know, so a personal vendetta type thing more than anything else.
And, you know, it.
It was, I don't know if it was all drug-related, but the drugs were very, very prevalent, especially when I was there.
They were trying to stand down and send people home, so they were actually running drug tests in the field.
